export const c5012_metadata = {dataset : "c5012", table_code : "C21501EQ", years : "2021 - 2021", start_year : "2021", end_year : "2021", geog_level : "ni", dataset_url : "https://data.nisra.gov.uk/table/C21501EQ", name : "Census Office", id : "EQGRP ECON_ACTIVITY_3", email : "census@nisra.gov.uk", subject : "Census", product : "Census 2021", title : "Economic activity", note : "Economic activity\n\nHow do we measure this?\n\nEconomically active: In employment (including full-time students)\nPeople aged 16 and over who were working in the week before census day.\n\nEconomically active: Unemployed (including full-time students)\nPeople aged 16 and over who were not in employment the week before census day and were looking for work and could start within two weeks, or waiting to start a job that had been offered and accepted.\n\nEconomically inactive\nPeople aged 16 and over who were not in employment the week before census day and were not looking for work or were looking for work but were not able to start in the next two weeks.\n\nAll\nAll people aged 16 and over\n\nSource\n[url=https://www.nisra.gov.uk/publications/census-2021-main-statistics-labour-market-tables]Census 2021[/url] contains further information on the labour market. More statistics can be found on the [url=https://www.nisra.gov.uk/statistics/2021-census/results]Census 2021 results page[/url].\n\nFurther information\r\n\nCensus 2021 included a suite of questions which were asked of everyone aged 16 and over to determine their economic status. This information led to a three-way classification of economic status:\n\nEconomically active: in employment (an employee, self-employed or full-time student in employment).\n\nEconomically active: unemployed (those who were looking for work and could start within two weeks, or waiting to start a job that had been offered and accepted).\n\nEconomically inactive: (those who did not have a job between 15 March and 21 March 2021 and had not looked for work between 22 February and 21 March 2021 or could not start within two weeks).\n\nThose who were economically inactive were recorded as one of the following statuses: retired, studying,\nlooking after home or family, long-term sick or disabled, or other.\n\nThese accredited official statistics were independently reviewed by the Office for Statistics Regulation in May 2022. They comply with the standards of trustworthiness, quality and value in the [url=https://code.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/]Code of Practice for Statistics[/url] and should be labelled ‘accredited official statistics’.\n\nAccredited official statistics are called National Statistics in the [url=https://osr.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/accredited-official-statistics/]Statistics and Registration Service Act 2007.[/url]\n\nSection 75 category: Age\nVariable used: Age\nBreakdown available:: 16-24; 25-34; 35-44; 45-54; 55-64; 65-74; 75+\n\nSection 75 category: Men and women generally\nVariable used: Sex\nBreakdown available:: Female; Male\n\nSection 75 category: Marital status\nVariable used: Marital and civil partnership status \nBreakdown available:: Single (never married or never in a legally registered civil partnership); Married or in a legally registered civil partnership; Separated or in a legally-recognised civil partnership and separated from civil partner; Divorced or formerly a civil partner, the civil partnership now legally dissolved; A surviving member of a legally registered civil partnership, Widowed.\n\nThis question is only asked if aged 16 or over.\n\nSection 75 category: Persons with a disability and persons without\nVariable used: Long-term health problem or disability\nBreakdown available:: Disabled; Not Disabled\n\n‘Disability’ is measured using ‘limiting long-standing illness’. Respondents are defined as having a limiting long standing illness if they have any physical or mental health conditions or illnesses lasting or expected to last for 12 months or more, and the condition(s) or illness(es) reduce their ability to carry out day to day activities.\n\nSection 75 category: Religious belief\nVariable used: Religion\nBreakdown available:: Catholic; Protestant and other Christian religions; Other religions; No religion/religion not stated\n\n[u]Catholic includes[/u]: Those who gave their current religion as Catholic or Roman Catholic.\n\n[u]Protestant and other Christian religions includes[/u]: Church of Ireland/Anglican/Episcopal; Baptist; Methodist; Presbyterian; Free Presbyterian; Brethren; United Reform Church (URC)/Congregational; Pentecostal; Church of Scotland; Elim Pentecostal; Reformed Presbyterian; Non-subscribing Presbyterian; Salvation Army; Church of Nazarene; Jehovah's Witness; Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Mormon); Other Protestant; Other Christian.\n\n[u]Other religions includes:[/u] Hindu; Jewish; Islam/Muslim; Sikh; Buddhist, Other.\n\nSection 75 category: Sexual orientation\nVariable used: Sexual orientation\nBreakdown available:: Straight or heterosexual; Gay, lesbian, bisexual or other sexual orientation; Prefer not to say or not stated\n\nThis question is only asked if aged 16 or over.\n\nSection 75 category: Dependants\nBreakdown available:: These data are not collected by census\n\nSection 75 category: Ethnic group\nBreakdown available: White; Irish traveller; Roma; Indian; Chinese; Filipino; Pakistani; Arab; Other Asian; Black African; Black other; Mixed; Other\n\nSection 75 category: Political opinion\nBreakdown available:: These data are not collected by census"};
