export const econ_further_information = ["'Economic inactivity rate excluding students' refers to the percentage of people aged 16-64 who are inactive for any reason other than being a student.\r\n\r\nTypically, the Office for National Statistics (ONS) would reweight the LFS every two years to take account of updated population estimates and projections. Since the onset of the pandemic, the ONS have been monitoring the impact, and as a result, there have been five LFS reweightings to improve the estimates. The latest reweighting was introduced in December 2024, affecting data from January-March 2019 to July-September 2024, to make use of more recent population estimates. An overview of the impact of reweighting on the NI estimates of unemployment, employment, and economic inactivity is available on the <a href='https://www.nisra.gov.uk/publications/background-information-lfs'>NISRA website</a>. Previous reweightings occurred in October 2020, July 2021, June 2022 and February 2024. The economic inactivity rate at the Northern Ireland level increased slightly in 2020 but has since returned to a level similar to the rates seen before the pandemic."];
export const econ_metadata = {dataset : "ECON", table_code : "ECONInullCTEQ", years : "2006 - 2024", start_year : "2006", end_year : "2024", geog_level : "ni", dataset_url : "https://data.nisra.gov.uk/table/ECONInullCTEQ", name : "Economic and Labour Market Statistics", id : "EQGRP", email : "economicstats@nisra.gov.uk", subject : "Labour market status", product : "Unemployed", title : "Economic inactivity", note : "Economic inactivity rate excluding students\r\n\r\nHow do we measure this?\r\nPercentage of the population aged 16 to 64 who are economically inactive for any reason other than being a student.\r\n\r\nSource\r\n[url=https://www.nisra.gov.uk/statistics/labour-market-and-social-welfare/labour-force-survey]Labour Force Survey, Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency[/url]\r\n\r\nFurther information\r\n'Economic inactivity rate excluding students' refers to the percentage of people aged 16-64 who are inactive for any reason other than being a student.\r\n\r\nTypically, the Office for National Statistics (ONS) would reweight the LFS every two years to take account of updated population estimates and projections. Since the onset of the pandemic, the ONS have been monitoring the impact, and as a result, there have been five LFS reweightings to improve the estimates. The latest reweighting was introduced in December 2024, affecting data from January-March 2019 to July-September 2024, to make use of more recent population estimates. An overview of the impact of reweighting on the NI estimates of unemployment, employment, and economic inactivity is available on the [url=https://www.nisra.gov.uk/publications/background-information-lfs]NISRA website[/url]. Previous reweightings occurred in October 2020, July 2021, June 2022 and February 2024. The economic inactivity rate at the Northern Ireland level increased slightly in 2020 but has since returned to a level similar to the rates seen before the pandemic.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Age\r\nVariable used: Age\r\nBreakdown available: 16-24; 25-34; 35-49; 50-64\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Men and women generally\r\nVariable used: Sex\r\nBreakdown available: Female; Male\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Marital status\r\nVariable used: Marital status\r\nBreakdown available: Single; Married/Civil partnership; Separated; Divorced; Widowed\r\n\r\nData is currently only available up to 2019. Data for 2020 – 2024 may be available following the 2025 annual tables.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Persons with a disability and persons without\r\nVariable used: Disability\r\nBreakdown available: Disabled; Not Disabled\r\n\r\nThese data use the Government Statistical Service (GSS) harmonised standard definition of disability. 'Disability' refers to those reporting (current) physical or mental health condition(s) or illnesses lasting or expected to last 12 months or more; and that the condition(s) or illness(es) reduce their ability to carry out day-to-day activities.\r\nData is provided from the first year available (2014).\r\nData is currently only available up to 2019. Data for 2020 – 2024 may be available following the 2025 annual tables.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Religious belief\r\nVariable used: Religion\r\nBreakdown available: Catholic; Protestant; Other/no religion\r\n\r\nData is provided from the first year available (2009).\r\nData is currently only available up to 2019. Data for 2020 – 2024 may be available following the 2025 annual tables.\r\n'Other' includes those who stated a religion other than Catholic and Protestant, those who stated no religion, those who refused to answer the question, and those whose answer was missing.\r\n\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Persons with dependants and persons without\r\nVariable used: Dependants\r\nBreakdown available: Has dependants; Does not have dependants\r\n\r\nFor this indicator, 'has dependants' includes those who are the head of the family or the wife/spouse of the head of the family who have any number of children under the age of 19.\r\nInformation on dependants is based on household level information. This dataset uses a different weighting methodology compared with the person-level dataset. Further information is available in Volume 1, Section 10.5 of the [url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/methodologies/labourforcesurveyuserguidance]Labour Force Survey – user guidance[/url].\r\nData is currently only available up to 2019. Data for 2020 – 2024 may be available following the 2025 annual tables. \r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Racial group\r\nVariable used: Ethnic group\r\nBreakdown available: White; Other\r\n\r\nDue to small sample sizes, racial groups other than white have been combined. Some figures within this category have been suppressed due to small sample sizes.\r\n'Other’ includes: Irish Traveller, Mixed/Multiple ethnic groups, Asian/Asian British, Black/African/Caribbean/Black British, Chinese, Arab, other ethnic groups.\r\nData is provided from the first year available (2013).\r\nData is currently only available up to 2019. Data for 2020 – 2024 may be available following the 2025 annual tables."};
