export const self_source_url = ["https://www.executiveoffice-ni.gov.uk/topics/statistics-and-research/individual-wellbeing-northern-ireland"];
export const self_further_information = ["Self-efficacy is defined as a person’s belief about their capabilities to exercise influence over events that affect their lives.\r\n\r\nThose with low self-efficacy often doubt their capabilities, are less ambitious and give up on aims when challenged. This can limit the choices a person makes and how much effort they are willing to invest.\r\n\r\nThe tool for measuring self-efficacy is a simple statement-based survey tool. It takes the form of five simple statements to which the individual indicates to what extent they agree or disagree on a five-point Likert scale. Self-efficacy is then presented as an overall score, minimum 5 and maximum 25, taken from the summed total of the five statement questions. Self-efficacy scores of 70% or more of the total possible score (i.e. 18 to 25) are categorised as high self-efficacy; low self-efficacy is therefore anything under 70% of the total possible score (i.e. 5 to 17).\r\n\r\nData refers to the percentage of the population aged 16 and over.\r\n\r\nSome figures have been suppressed due to small sample sizes (less than 100 respondents).\r\nAll estimates for mean scores and percentages are based on weighted data and have been rounded to one decimal place.\r\n\r\nThe coronavirus pandemic resulted in a change in data collection mode and a reduced sample size for 2020/21. Users should therefore take this into consideration when interpreting any subsequent years of data, and care should be taken when comparing findings published prior to 2020/21.\r\n\r\nData is collected through Continuous Household Survey (CHS).\r\n\r\nThe sample size for 2017/18, 2018/19 and 2019/20 was approximately double that of previous years.\r\n\r\nSome figures have been suppressed due to small sample sizes (less than 100 respondents), missing values are denoted as ‘..’ or a blank space depending on the format it is being viewed."];
export const self_metadata = {dataset : "SELF", table_code : "SELFEFFEQ", years : "2014/15 - 2024/25", start_year : "2014/15", end_year : "2024/25", geog_level : "ni", dataset_url : "https://data.nisra.gov.uk/table/SELFEFFEQ", name : "PfG Analytics, The Executive Office", id : "EQGRP", email : "pfganalytics@executiveoffice-ni.gov.uk", subject : "Individual wellbeing", product : "Self-efficacy", title : "Low self-efficacy", note : "Low self-efficacy\r\n\r\nHow do we measure this?\r\nPercentage of people categorised as having low self-efficacy (or low confidence in their own abilities). Self-efficacy is defined as a persons belief about their capabilities to exercise influence over events that affect their lives. For this indicator a lower figure is better.\r\n\r\nSource\r\n[url=https://www.executiveoffice-ni.gov.uk/topics/statistics-and-research/individual-wellbeing-northern-ireland]Individual Wellbeing in Northern Ireland, The Executive Office[/url]\r\n\r\nFurther information\r\nSelf-efficacy is defined as a person’s belief about their capabilities to exercise influence over events that affect their lives.\r\n\r\nThose with low self-efficacy often doubt their capabilities, are less ambitious and give up on aims when challenged. This can limit the choices a person makes and how much effort they are willing to invest.\r\n\r\nThe tool for measuring self-efficacy is a simple statement-based survey tool. It takes the form of five simple statements to which the individual indicates to what extent they agree or disagree on a five-point Likert scale. Self-efficacy is then presented as an overall score, minimum 5 and maximum 25, taken from the summed total of the five statement questions. Self-efficacy scores of 70% or more of the total possible score (i.e. 18 to 25) are categorised as high self-efficacy; low self-efficacy is therefore anything under 70% of the total possible score (i.e. 5 to 17).\r\n\r\nData refers to the percentage of the population aged 16 and over.\r\n\r\nSome figures have been suppressed due to small sample sizes (less than 100 respondents).\r\nAll estimates for mean scores and percentages are based on weighted data and have been rounded to one decimal place.\r\n\r\nThe coronavirus pandemic resulted in a change in data collection mode and a reduced sample size for 2020/21. Users should therefore take this into consideration when interpreting any subsequent years of data, and care should be taken when comparing findings published prior to 2020/21.\r\n\r\nData is collected through Continuous Household Survey (CHS).\r\n\r\nThe sample size for 2017/18, 2018/19 and 2019/20 was approximately double that of previous years.\r\n\r\nSome figures have been suppressed due to small sample sizes (less than 100 respondents), missing values are denoted as ‘..’ or a blank space depending on the format it is being viewed.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Age\r\nVariable used: Age\r\nBreakdown available: 16-24; 25-34; 35-49; 50-64; 65-74; 75+\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Men and women generally\r\nVariable used: Sex\r\nBreakdown available: Female; Male\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Marital status\r\nVariable used: Marital status\r\nBreakdown available: Single; Married/Civil partnership; Separated; Divorced; Widowed \r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Persons with a disability and persons without\r\nVariable used: Disability\r\nBreakdown available: Disabled; Not Disabled\r\n\r\n[u]‘Disability’[/u] is measured using ‘limiting long-standing illness’. Respondents are defined as having a limiting long standing illness if they have any physical or mental health conditions or illnesses lasting or expected to last for 12 months or more, and the condition(s) or illness(es) reduce their ability to carry out day to day activities.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Religious belief\r\nVariable used: Religion \r\nBreakdown available: Catholic; Protestant and other Christian religions; Other/no religion\r\n\r\n[u]‘Other/no religion'[/u] includes those who stated a religion other than Catholic and Protestant, those who stated no religion, those who refused to answer the question, and those whose answer was missing.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Sexual orientation\r\nVariable used: Sexual orientation\r\nBreakdown available: Straight or heterosexual; Gay, lesbian, bisexual or other sexual orientation \r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Persons with dependants and persons without\r\nVariable used: Dependants\r\nBreakdown available: Has dependants; Does not have dependants\r\n\r\n[u]‘Has dependants’[/u] includes individuals who have responsibility for the care of: a child(ren); a person with a disability; and/or a dependant elderly person.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Racial group\r\nVariable used: Ethnic Group\r\nBreakdown available: White; Other\r\n\r\n[u]‘Other'[/u] includes: 'Irish Traveller'; 'White and Black Caribbean'; 'White and Black African'; 'White and Asian'; 'Any other mixed/multiple ethnic background'; 'Indian'; 'Pakistani'; 'Bangladeshi'; 'Chinese'; 'Any other Asian background'; 'African'; 'Caribbean'; 'Any other Black/African/Caribbean background'; 'Arab'; and 'Any other ethnic group'.\r\n\r\nSection 75 category: Political opinion\r\nBreakdown available: These data are not collected by the survey"};
